Diagnosis.
Females are immediately identifiable for their enlarged, somewhat pointed scoop-like mandibles and almost complete lack of an inferior tooth, with no more than a weak ridge along top edge (
Fig. 41F
). If the mandibles are worn, which is common, then they are distinctly flattened apically. Females may be otherwise determined by the following character combination: galea tessellate, dull; clypeal maculation a band of variable thickness along rim, medially extending upward to a point (
Fig. 41F
); T1 covered in appressed setae; T2–T4 with relatively broad apical appressed setal bands, weakly to strongly undulate; T5 with appressed setae, of varying amounts; and anal fimbria blackish. Males may be determined by the following character combination: galea tessellate, dull; scape immaculate; T2–T6 with apical appressed setal bands; T7 lacking medial longitudinal ridge, lateral projections distinct and sharp, and medial projections about as sharp as lateral projections (
Fig. 61F
).

Male description.
Head: Facial maculations pale yellow to yellow-green. Galea reaching front to middle of foretrochanter in repose; medium to dark brown; strongly to moderately tessellate, with weak reflections. Mandible with inferior tooth ridge-like and nearly fully attached to main blade, running parallel to it; maculated from base to start or middle of inferior tooth (
Fig. 51F
). Labral rim tridentate; fully maculated. Clypeal maculation a thin band, not reaching lateral sides, sometimes pointed upward, filling a third to half the height of the clypeus (
Fig. 51F
); punctation moderately sparser within maculation than without. Paraocular area immaculate. Supraclypeal area immaculate. Scape immaculate. Mesosoma: Scutum shiny; with impunctate areas, sometimes invaded by sparse punctures. Tegula transparent to translucent, light to dark brown. Basitibial plate usually absent; rarely weakly present, obscured by setae if so. Metasoma: T1 with slight apical appressed setal band, setae sparser basally; T2–T6 with apical setal bands, often weak on T6. Terga strongly to moderately tessellate between punctures, only weakly reflective if at all; not apparent through appressed setae. Tergal rims transparent, tan to light brown. Male T7 (
Fig. 61F
) without medial longitudinal carina, rarely weakly present as impunctate line rather than raised carina; lateral projections strongly recurved, sharp; medial projections relatively thin, tips relatively sharp. Male S5 (
Figs. 38A, 38C
) setal arrangement unremarkable, without large, distinctive patches, at most longer along rim. Male S6 (
Fig. 38A
) clearly medially emarginate. Male S7 (
Fig. 66F
) with setae absent or nearly so around midpoint of length; widening from midpoint to tip, apical half widest at pointed lateral tips; apical half vaguely resembling owl head, rim broadly emarginate between lateral tips. Male S8 (
Fig. 71F
) lateral projections distinct; medial projection narrowing to tip, apically emarginate. Male genital capsule (
Fig. 76F
) with outer corners, where gonocoxite tips curve inward, marked by low flange without clear angle, best seen in profile; from corner to apex, in profile, gonocoxite with two slight bumps and distinct concavity before tip; tip, in profile, rounded and moderately curved ventrally, with minor dorsal projection clearly pointed; gonostylus tip position slightly exceeding that of gonocoxite, measured from above along primary axis of latter. Pubescence: See 

Fig. 
56F

. Appears dark gray overall, sometimes brownish. Setae slightly tan to dorsally and lighter toward venter, except as follows: vertex and scutum often, but not always, with some dark intermixed; leg inner faces orange; tergal basal zones dark.

Nesting biology.
Anthophora peritomae
has been recorded nesting vertically in both tightly-packed sand and sandstone ( Torchio 1971 ;
Orr et al . 2016
). Further details on these new records will be presented in a subsequent review of the group’s nesting biology.
